Preamble
--------
This document exists primarily so that everyone may feel comfortable that
there *is* a license, which is widely regarded as an important thing for a
piece of software to possess. However, the Faculty has long held the opinion
that serious legal matters are best handled by people who enjoy that sort of
thing, preferably in another file.

Accordingly, this license concerns itself mainly with good manners,
scholarly sharing, and the general encouragement of digital thaumaturgy.

Definitions
-----------
"Grimoire" shall refer to this software and any associated documentation,
scripts, diagrams, mysterious comments in the source code, or other arcane
materials bundled alongside it.

"Practitioner of Digital Thaumaturgy" shall refer to any individual, group,
guild, or sufficiently self-aware automaton who obtains a copy of the
Grimoire.

Grant of Permission
-------------------
Permission is hereby granted, free of charge, to any practitioner of digital
thaumaturgy obtaining a copy of this software and associated documentation
files (the "Grimoire"), to deal in the Grimoire without restriction,
including without limitation the rights to use, copy, modify, merge,
publish, distribute, sublicense, and/or sell copies of the Grimoire, and to
permit persons to whom the Grimoire is furnished to do so.

The Faculty generally encourages such activity, provided that it does not
explode the University, the city, or the surrounding countryside.

Conditions
----------
1. The above copyright notice and this permission notice shall be included in
   all copies or substantial portions of the Grimoire, preferably intact and
   not hidden behind suspiciously small font sizes.

2. Where any other license file exists within this repository (including but
   not limited to MIT, Apache 2.0, BSD, GPL, or any license yet to be
   invented by the Department of Post-Mortem Communications), said license
   shall take precedence over this one in all matters of legal specificity,
   enforceability, and terrifyingly precise wording.

3. In the absence of such a license, readers are encouraged to behave in the
   spirit of collegial scholarship: share improvements, avoid unnecessary
   villainy, and do not claim authorship unless you actually wrote the
   thing.*

4. The Archchancellor reserves the right to alter these terms at any time,
   particularly around mealtimes, after long lunches, or when feeling
   magnanimous.

   *This clause has historically proven difficult for wizards.

